The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                Heroin worth Rs 1 crore was seized from two youths who were arrested at Mullickpur railway station, on the southern city fringes, on Monday night. Pintu Debnath and Mohammad Khan, residents of Nandigram and Mahishadal in East Midnapore, were rounded up after they got off a local train with 1.4 kg heroin. The two in their 20s were to hand over the consignment to a person whom we are yet to trace, said Dilip Mitra, the additional director-general of police, railways.  quot; The two were carrying the consignment from Raghunandanpur, a place between Mecheda and Nandigram in East Midnapore. We are conducting raids to arrest the other members of the gang, he said.  quot; The duo said during interrogation that they were to hand over the consignment to a person in Narendrapur, a GRP officer said.     Power tripped on the sixth floor of the Academy Building of RG Kar Medical hospital during the launch of an MRI unit on Tuesday. The glitch was repaired in seven minutes but health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra had to deliver his speech in darkness. RG Kar medical superintendent Lalit Vaid said an MRI scan in the hospital would cost Rs 2,490, the lowest in the country.																																																								  quot;Ten per cent of the patients coming for an MRI scan will be provided the service free if they are poor, he added. Finance minister Asim Dasgupta attended the programme.     Three girls allegedly hanged themselves in different parts of the city on Tuesday. Ganga Das, a Class X student of ML Pal High School in Hooghly, was found hanging in her Girish Park house. Police said she had failed to clear her board exams and had been suffering from depression.																																																		  Farhat Khatun, 15, was found hanging in her Panchpara house in Howrah. Manmohini Das, 25, was found hanging in her Jagachha home in Howrah. All three bodies have been sent for post-mortem.     A girl and a boy were run over by a local train near Palta railway station, on the citys northern fringes, on Tuesday. Police said the mishap occurred around 5pm when Rasia Khatun, 22, and an unidentified youth in his 30s were crossing the tracks without noticing an approaching Kalyani-bound train. The girl, a resident of Palta, was identified from the documents she was carrying.    A 54-year-old security guard of a closed factory in Howrah was found dead on the factory premises on Andul Road early on Tuesday. Police said Chinmoy Nandi and two other guards had tried to stop five men from stealing scrap from the factory compound. The armed gang beat up Nandi, who died on the spot. His colleagues managed to flee.    A 30-year-old youth died after a speeding bus knocked him down at the Panchla crossing on National Highway 6 on Tuesday noon. Police said Samar Das, a resident of Dhamisha in Panchla, Howrah, was crossing the highway on a bicycle when the bus hit him. The vehicle then lost control and fell into a water body. Around 20 passengers of the bus were injured.    A Druk flight from Bangkok to Paro carrying 84 passengers was diverted to Calcutta airport on Tuesday morning because of bad weather at the Bhutanese destination, airport officials said. The flight landed at Calcutta airport at 9.30am and took off an hour later after the weather improved.     The principal of Julien Day School (Ganganagar) is N. McNamara, not J.K. Sen as mentioned in Metro in the report Care for rules without cane on July 10. The error is regretted.             
